# CLI: Use Click

All command-line interfaces must be built with [Click](https://click.palletsprojects.com/). Never use `argparse`, `sys.argv` parsing, or other CLI libraries.

## Define Commands with Decorators

Expose the entry point as a Click command and declare arguments and options with decorators.

```python
# ✅ GOOD — Click command with a typed option
import click


@click.command()
@click.option("--config-path", required=True, help="Path to the training config.")
def train(config_path: str):
    config = GhostConfig.create(config_path)
    run_training(config)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    train()
```

```python
# ❌ BAD — argparse
import argparse


def main():
    parser = argparse.ArgumentParser()
    parser.add_argument("--config-path", required=True)
    arguments = parser.parse_args()
    run_training(GhostConfig.create(arguments.config_path))
```

## Group Related Commands

Use `@click.group()` to collect related subcommands under one entry point.

```python
@click.group()
def cli():
    pass


@cli.command()
@click.option("--config-path", required=True)
def train(config_path: str):
    ...


@cli.command()
@click.option("--checkpoint-path", required=True)
def evaluate(checkpoint_path: str):
    ...
```
